<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Affirms Acceptance of Haitians </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Affirms Acceptance of Haitians </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0306210294 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1943 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0306210294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN

  [Text] Caracas, 3 Jun (EFE) -- Venezuelan Foreign Minister
Miguel Angel Burelli said here today that Venezuela has agreed
to receive Haitian refugees on the condition that they comprise
only a small number of refugees who would remain in Venezuela
temporarily, until the crisis in the Antillean nation is
resolved.
  The Venezuelan Government's decision was announced after an
official U.S. delegation headed by Under Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott asked the government of Venezuelan President
Rafael Caldera to accept Haitian refugees.
  The U.S. official called the Venezuelan offer "generous,"
and
he recalled that Caracas had received the very first Haitian
refugee--President Jean-Bertrand Aristide who was received by
Venezuela after he was overthrown in September 1991. Talbott
reiterated that his government wants a "peaceful and
multilateral" solution to the Haitian crisis.
  Burelli told newsmen that Venezuela "has informed the United
States that it will not close its doors and that it will receive
a group (of Haitians), provided they are temporary refugees who
will remain until the precarious situation in Haiti is resolved."
  The foreign minister explained that the Venezuelan Embassy
in
Washington will list the number of Haitians eligible to travel
to Venezuela as an "undetermined number," although "this cannot
be a large number."

</TEXT>

