<H3> <TI>   Government Denies Venezuelan Foray Into Brazilian Soil </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1902010694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1648 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1902010694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN

  [Text] Brasilia, 18 Feb (EFE) -- The Brazilian Foreign
Ministry has denied an alleged Venezuelan military foray inside
Brazilian territory in the Amazon region.
  Brazilian Foreign Ministry sources in Brasilia said the
information regarding an incursion by Venezuelan National Guard
troops to capture Brazilian "garimpeiros" (illegal miners) is
"absurd."
  The Brazilian Foreign Ministry has not been informed about
the possible detention of "garimpeiros" by Venezuelan
authorities, even though the possibility cannot be ruled out,
the sources added.
  Entrepreneur Jose Altino Machado, who owns machinery for the
illegal mining of minerals in the Amazon region, said that last
week the Venezuelan National Guard entered Brazilian territory
to capture 32 "garimpeiros" and the "garimpeiros" were later
taken to the Venezuelan city of Puerto Ayacucho.
  In the past few years dozens of Brazilian "garimpeiros" have
been arrested by the National Guard on charges of illegal mining
of gold and other minerals in Venezuela. On some occasions
authorities were able to confirm reports of Venezuelan forays
inside Brazilian territory.
  Brazil and Venezuela share a common border 2,000 km long
that
is sparsely controlled, has minimal communications, and few
settlements.
  According to officials sources, the problem of illegal
mining, the protection of indigenous populations, and the Amazon
region's development will be discussed during an official visit
Brazilian President Itamar Franco will make to Venezuela between
3 and 5 March.
  Franco will travel to Venezuela at the invitation of
Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera.

</TEXT>

