<H3> <TI>   Venezuela To Raise Poverty Issue at Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2103131594 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0713 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2103131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN

  [Text] Brasilia, 21 Mar (EFE) -- Venezuelan Foreign
Minister Miguel Angel Burelli told EFE today in Brasilia that
the eradication of poverty must be "the number one issue" at the
continental summit called by U.S. President Bill Clinton for
December in Miami (United States).
  The Venezuelan minister said he believes Clinton's
initiative
is of "supreme interest" as a way to develop new relations
between the United States and Latin America following the end of
the Cold War.
  Burelli said: "We hope the schedule" for the Miami summit
"will be established soon." Burelli will participate in a
48-hour meeting of foreign ministers and governmental
representatives from 13 Rio Group countries that begins today at
Itamaraty, the Brazilian Foreign Ministry headquarters.
  This summit will allow an exchange of opinions toward
consensus among Latin American governments before the summit
called by President Clinton, and to review the international
situation.
  The ministers will establish the bases for two upcoming Rio
Group summits: the talks that are held twice a year with the EC
foreign ministers -- scheduled for 20-23 April in Sao Paulo --
and the Eighth Annual Rio Group summit scheduled for 8-9
September in Rio de Janeiro.
  Even though it is not on the agenda, the delegates will use
the meeting to probe preferences for the election of a new OAS
secretary general on 27 March in Washington.
  Diplomatic sources have stated that this issue will crop up
in lobby talks and even in the Rio Group's three flexible
sessions as any delegation head is allowed to raise it.
  Foreign Minister Burelli is one of the candidates for the
OAS
General Secretariat, replacing Brazilian diplomat Joao Baena
Soares, whose five-year term ends in June.
  Colombian President Cesar Gaviria and Costa Rican Foreign
Minister Bernd Niehaus are also running.
  Foreign Minister Burelli indicated that the Rio Group must
forge "a social bias" for Latin American policy because "the
people eagerly want consideration in the decision-making
process."
  Burelli said: "Poverty represents a new scourge within
society as it has new elements of insecurity that cannot be
fought with armies. It is tied to hunger, terrorism, drug
trafficking, violence, and growing destitution."
  Burelli said that internal and external migration in Latin
American countries has helped to form "pockets" of misery in
large cities. He mentioned the migration from rural areas and
the arrival of about 60,000 Guyanese citizens in Venezuela.
They become involved in the underground economy.
  The people responsible for regional diplomacy will assess a
preliminary document entitled: "Poverty, Destitution, and
Unemployment." This document was compiled at the Rio Group's
request by experts from various governments, the Economic
Commission for Latin America (ECLA), and the United Nations.
  The document proposes guidelines to cure the phenomena and
will become a Rio Group's contribution for the UN Conference on
Social Development scheduled for 1995 in the city of Copenhagen.

</TEXT>

