<H3> <TI>   Presidents, Officials React to Castro Speech </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidents, Officials React to Castro Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Venezuela Urges Cuban Democracy </H4>

<F P=102> PA1506221594 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1831 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1506221594 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN

  [Text] Cartagena de Indias (Colombia), 14 Jun (EFE) --
Venezuelan Foreign Affairs Minister Miguel Angel Burelli said
today that should Cuba want to join the OAS, it must comply with
the rule of democracy, hold elections, and respect human rights.
  Burelli told the media gathered at the Convention Center of
Cartagena de Indias (Colombia), where the Fourth Ibero-American
Summit is taking place on 14 and 15 June, "America is a
community that has a political system established by the OAS;
there is a government philosophy and a rule of democracy."
  He pointed out: "For Cuba to belong to this community, it
must comply with the rule of democracy; that is, it must hold
elections and respect human rights." He also pointed out he
hopes Cuban President Fidel Castro "takes the necessary steps to
join the community that is waiting for him."
  Answering a question on whether Castro's move from wearing
his green military uniform to wearing a guayabera shirt could be
interpreted as a his willingness to make changes, Burelli
replied: "I hope so!; I hope so!" This is the first time Castro
has dressed in something other than his uniform since the Cuban
Revolution succeeded in 1959. The Venezuelan foreign minister
stressed his government "is very interested" in the Cuban
economic changes, but it hopes these changes come along with
"political changes."
  During the summit's first session, Venezuelan President
Rafael Caldera said: "The time has come" for Cuba to join the
inter-American political and judicial systems and to change its
political system.
  Minister Burelli said the opposite with regard to Haiti: His
government opposes any "unilateral or multilateral" military
action in Haiti to put and end to the bitter crisis that is
engulfing that country. Burelli also reported his government
has requested the inclusion of the issue of corruption in the
summit agenda in order to issue a resolution to prevent
"granting asylum to corrupt people, just as drug traffickers are
denied asylum."

</TEXT>

