<F P=102>   PA2904042294 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1507 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2904042294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN

  [Text] Caracas, 26 Apr (EFE) -- Venezuelan Foreign Minister
Miguel Angel Burelli has announced the creation of the
Association of Caribbean States, which he defined as an
important step within the process of regional integration.
Burelli, who made the announcement on Monday when he dedicated
the Department of Latin America and the Caribbean at the Central
University of Venezuela (UCV), explained that the association
will include all of the Caribbean states and will begin work on
4 July.
  As of 1969 and following the process of independence of the
countries forming part of Caribbean Common Market, Venezuela
designed an "unchanging policy of lending a hand" to these
nations with the sole purpose of serving its neighbors, the
foreign minister emphasized. Venezuela is the only country that
has 12 embassies and 10 cultural centers in the Caribbean. It
also signed the San Jose Pact with Mexico, which supplies
petroleum to those nations under special payment conditions. In
addition, the government in Caracas has signed a Caribbean
Development Bank exchange program that allows the granting of
recoverable lines of credit to the Caribbean countries.
  The Venezuelan foreign minister expressed his support for a
massive Venezuelan projection into the Caribbean that, with the
exception of Trinidad-Tobago and Guyana, is made up of small
nations without large resources and with a small population.

</TEXT>

