<F P=102>   PA1405182094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1718 GMT 14 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1405182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN

  [Text] Caracas, 14 May (EFE) -- Venezuela will not support
a military intervention in Haiti, a Foreign Ministry spokesman
said today in Caracas. The government, however, supports
pressure tactics to restore democracy in that Caribbean nation.
  According to the spokesman, Venezuela will not join any
armed
multinational force or support a unilateral decision by the
United States if that country decides to intervene in Haiti.
  Venezuela is the only Latin American country that belongs to
the Group of Friends of Haiti, which comprises the United
States, France, and Canada.
  The possibility of an armed intervention in Haiti has gained
strength after the military who toppled head of state
Jean-Bertrand Aristide appointed a puppet president. This week
the military, led by Raoul Cedras, who headed the coup,
appointed Supreme Court Justice Emile Jonassaint president,
something the United Nations and the OAS have rejected. The
United Nations agreed to tighten the economic sanctions on the
Haitian military regime as of 21 May.

</TEXT>

