<H3> <TI>   Rio Group Foreign Ministers Continue Meeting </TI></H3>
<H4>   Doubts Expressed Over Miami as Summit Site </H4>
<F P=102> PY2303003994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2129 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2303003994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN

  [Text] Brasilia, 22 Mar (EFE) -- Diplomatic source told EFE
News Agency that some Rio Group foreign ministers -- who have
been holding talks in Brasilia for the last two days --
expressed certain reservations about the U.S. proposal that
Miami should host the next summit of the Americas convened by
the United States.
  Although the heads of Latin American diplomacy were
enthusiastic about U.S. President Bill Clinton's proposal, some
of them expounded the "inadvisability" of holding the summit in
Miami, where anti-Castro groups have a lot of clout.
  The diplomats who assisted at the Brasilia meeting, which
ended today, told EFE that the issue was discussed at the
meeting, but did not disclose what delegations were opposed to
Miami being the venue for the summit meeting.
  The reservations stem from the fear that anti-Castro groups
will harass some heads of state on account of the independent
stance adopted by their countries and the Rio Group concerning
the U.S. policy vis-a-vis Cuba.
  The reservations seemingly reached the ears of U.S. Vice
President Albert Gore, who made a seven-hour visit to Brasilia
-- which extended from the evening of 21 March to the early
hours of 22 March -- to invite Brazilian President Itamar Franco
to the Miami summit.
  After the Rio Group meeting, Brazilian Foreign Minister
Celso
Amorim said Gore guaranteed him that matters alien to the summit
-- alluding to anti-Castro Cubans -- will not interfere in its
organization and agenda.
  Amorim noted that it is "too early" to say whether Cuba's
political and economic situation will be included on the
December summit's agenda.
  He further stated that both the summit's date and venue
depend on the decision of the U.S. Government, which convened
the meeting.
  Venezuelan Foreign Minister Miguel Angel Burelli commented
that, in his view, Miami was not a "risky" place to bring
together all the heads of state in the Americas.
  Several Rio Group foreign ministers praised the flexibility
of the issues proposed by Clinton, who has asked governments to
offer suggestions to complete the agenda.
  The subjects put forward by Clinton to his Western
Hemisphere
counterparts include the strengthening of democracy, human
rights, trade, poverty, the environment, and the streamlining of
public administration.
  Paraguayan Foreign Minister Luis Maria Ramirez Boettner told
EFE that his country is interested in highlighting trade
liberalization, economic investments, and cooperation at the
summit. Burelli, for his part, noted that questions like
education, poverty, and access to technology had to be part of
the agenda.
  Despite the fact that they differ widely on the types of
pressure that should be exerted on Cuba so it will adopt a
pluralistic system to replace the single-party system, Rio Group
countries have condemned the trade embargo on Cuba imposed by
the United States more than 30 years ago.
  Brazil and Colombia recently have become the target of
criticism and threats by anti-Castro groups due to their stances
on the situation in Havana.

</TEXT>

