<H3> <TI>   Rio Group Foreign Ministers Open Brasilia Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2203000994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1734 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2203000994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN

  [Text] Brasilia, 21 Mar (EFE) -- The foreign ministers and
government representatives of the 13 member countries of the Rio
Group today began their 48-hour meeting in Brasilia, during
which they will discuss the international situation.
  During the three work meetings that will be held they will
establish the position of the Latin American governments
regarding the continental summit organized by U.S. President
Bill Clinton for December in Miami.
  Host Foreign Minister Celso Amorim said during the opening
ceremony that the delegations will discuss initiatives for
obtaining access to advanced technologies from developed
countries.
  The subject of poverty and unemployment in Latin America and
the functioning of the Rio Group will also be discussed, as will
the 1994 calendar of meetings, especially the meeting with the
foreign ministers of the European Union, which will take place
20-23 April in Sao Paulo, and the eighth annual summit to take
place in Rio de Janeiro 9-10 September.
  The foreign ministers will take the opportunity during the
meeting to sense preferences for the election to be held 27
March in Washington for OAS secretary general, replacing the
Brazilian Joao Baena Soares.
  The meeting is being attended by Foreign Ministers Celso
Amorim of Brazil, Manuel Tello of Mexico, Miguel Angel Burelli
of Venezuela, Antonio Aranibar of Bolivia, Carlos Figueroa of
Chile, Gladys de Vielman of Guatemala, Sergio Abreu of Uruguay,
Luis Maria Ramirez Boettner of Paraguay, and Ralph Moraj of
Trinidad and Tobago.
  Other delegations are represented by their deputy foreign
ministers: Jorge Gordillo of Peru, Andelfo Garcia of Colombia,
and Fernando Petrella of Argentina. The Ecuadoran delegation is
headed by Ecuadoran Ambassador to Brasilia Cesar Valdivieso.

</TEXT>

