  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 11 Jun (EFE) -- Today, the
organization known as "Capois-La-Mort," which includes
high-ranking extreme right-wing soldiers, demanded strict
measures against foreigners and the closure of the
Port-au-Prince and Cap-Haitiene airports. In addition, they
demanded an end to diplomatic relations with France, Canada,
Venezuela, and the United States and declared the ambassadors of
these countries persona non grata. According to their demands,
no foreign airplanes should be allowed to land at the Haitian
capital or at any other airport.
  The demands were listed in a communique issued today. Among
other things, the document asks for border officials to ban the
entry of foreigners crossing the Dominican Republic border. The
document also demands cutting off water, power, and telephone
services to foreign embassies and those "collaborating with the
enemy."
  The military group suggests and even demands giving the
French, Canadian, Venezuelan, and U.S. ambassadors 48 hours to
leave Haiti. If they choose to remain in the country, the group
recommends limiting their movements as well as the movements of
other diplomatic representatives, consuls, and members of
international agencies.
  They call for ambassadors and other foreign government
officials to be ordered to remain within a 15 km radius of their
official domicile. According to the communique outlining the
special measures, in order for these people to travel outside
the said 15 km perimeter, they must first get approval from the
Ministry of Foreign Relations and the Armed Forces.
  "Capois-La-Mort" considers the strict sanctions ordered
against the country and backed by the international community,
as "a declaration of war against the black Republic of Haiti."
The organization urges the government to approve special "war
measures," to enable it to respond to the "foreign aggression."
  The written demands presented by "Capois-La-Mort" come while
rumors of a foreign military invasion of Haiti spread.
Observers see the demands as evidence that the military and its
collaborators could take extreme measures.

</TEXT>

