Amazonian countries to join in this project. He said that
Colombia and Venezuela had shown interest in it and specified
that "it was a system for protection, not military defense," but
the Indians do not believe this.
  "We do not need the military to protect us. Thanks, anyway.
What we need is to be left alone, recognition our territories,
and the right to a large share of what is produced in them," the
COICA communique states. "We know you intend to militarize an
approximately 20-mile wide strip throughout thousands of
kilometers of the jungle, much of which is Indian territory,"
the communique adds. "If you divide the $1 billion you will
spend to `protect us' among the million Indians who live here,
that will give us $1,000 per person," the communique points out.
