<H3> <TI>   OAS Assembly Meeting Continues 8 Jun in Brazil </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OAS Assembly Meeting Continues 8 Jun in Brazil </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Council Head: `Do Not Rule Out' Intervention </H4>

<F P=102> PY0806224994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2128 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0806224994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN

  [Text] Belem do Para, 8 Jun (EFE) -- Today, OAS Permanent
Council President Denneth Modeste said the Caribbean member
countries of Caricom [Caribbean Common Market] have not ruled
out any option for reestablishing democracy in Haiti, including
military intervention.
  During a news conference in which he spoke on behalf of
Caricom members, Modeste said that "if the sanctions do not
attain the desired objective, we do not rule out any option" for
reestablishing democracy in Haiti, including the military option.
  "We believe the flagrant human rights violations against the
poor Haitian people have been going on for too long," Modeste
said, adding that before considering a military operation one
should wait for the strengthening of the embargo against the
Haitian coupists to see if this is effective.
  Modeste, who represents Grenada before the OAS, added that
the Caricom members have sent "a strong message to the Haitian
authorities, and we expect them to respect their people's will
to reestablish President Jean Bertrand Aristide in power."
  During the OAS General Assembly taking place in this
Brazilian coastal city, the foreign ministers of the OAS member
countries approved a resolution to intensify the trade embargo
against Haiti, asking for total compliance. Regarding the
express prohibition against launching armed action against other
countries, which is specified in the OAS Charter, Modeste said
"it did not prevent the reestablishment of democracy in Grenada
through military intervention." He said this in reference to
the U.S. invasion of Grenada in 1983. Modeste stressed the
democratic progress attained in Grenada, adding that "for this
reason Grenada does not rule out any action."
  Despite the call for admitting Haitian refugees, as
mentioned
in the resolution on Haiti, Modeste said the Caricom countries
cannot accept more of them because of the problems that many
Caribbean countries have in offering them assistance and
services.
  "The problem of the refugees reflects what is going on in
Haiti, and we must attempt to address the cause rather than the
effects, and the cause is human rights violations in Haiti,"
Modeste said.
  As for the possibility that Grenada could participate in a
possible military operation against the Haitian coupists, who
usurped power from Aristide in September 1991, Modeste said
Grenada "does not have an Army," but would be willing to help
train "a more responsible Haitian police" once the military
return power to Aristide.
  The Haitian crisis has been one of the central points
discussed at the OAS General Assembly, which began on 6 June and
could end tomorrow, a day earlier than scheduled, given the
swiftness with which the various committees advanced in their
work.

</TEXT>

