<H3> <TI>   Haitian Crisis Viewed as `Internal Matter' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Haitian Crisis Viewed as `Internal Matter' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1205203694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1856 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1205203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN

<F P=106> [By Alonso de Contreras] </F>
  [Text] Santo Domingo, 12 May (EFE) -- The illegal
appointment of Emile Jonassaint as Haitian president places the
Dominican Government in a new, truly uncomfortable position -- a
vantage point from which it has decided not to meddle in the
internal affairs of its neighboring country.
  Today, the Dominican Government distanced itself from
international criticism of the Haitian coupists for appointing
Jonassaint as the new Haitian president. The government declared
this was "an internal matter" and a new twist in a crisis the
Haitian people must resolve themselves.
  In statements to EFE, Dominican Foreign Minister Aristides
Taveras Guzman today said: "We understand the appointment... is
a move by the Haitian politicians, and, as a country that abides
by its government's policy, we respect the sovereignty and
integrity of the people."
  With the backing of the military that seized power in a
September 1991 coup, Supreme Court Magistrate Emile Jonassaint
assumed the presidency of Haiti on Wednesday, drawing criticism
from the international community and causing fears of armed
intervention from abroad.
  Aristides Guzman said: "Although we have endorsed OAS and UN
efforts to achieve the democratic transition of the (Haitian)
people, we have always stressed, in one way or another, that the
Haitians should be the sole protagonists in resolving their
problems."
  This position by the Dominican Government, according to what
Foreign Ministry officials admitted privately, reflects their
impotence in face of a Haitian crisis that has no good or
acceptable resolutions from a Dominican standpoint.
  The Dominican Republic is fated not to agree with but to
comply with UN and OAS sanctions against the Haitian military --
sanctions designed to return deposed President Jean Bertrand
Aristide to power. The Dominican Republic is hoping the crisis
will calmly die on its own, preferably by the end of the
constitutional term of the Haitian government-in-exile, which is
in February 1995.
  All current developments in the Haitian crisis are
threatening the Dominican Republic.
  Aristide was criticized because of his anti-Dominican
remarks
during the seven months he was in power. The military
government cannot be accepted, however, because of international
opposition, and the same is true for the illegal appointment of
Emile Jonaissant.
  The economic embargo imposed by the United Nations and the
OAS has not resolved the problem and has discredited the
Dominican Armed Forces, which have been unable to prevent
smuggling across the border. The new embargo, which will be
implemented on 21 May, puts more responsibility on Dominican
surveillance and will require additional spending. The number
of Haitian exiles and refugees are increasing in the Dominican
Republic, while the Dominican Government is resisting pressure
to install refugee camps near the border. The Dominican
Republic also has been obliged to accept international
observers, who will arrive this week to oversee the fulfillment
of the embargo.
  All of these problems were outlined to EFE today by Deputy
Foreign Minister Fabio Herrera Cabral, who confirmed the
acceptance of international observers, but he reiterated that
"the embargo violates the Haitian people's human rights. He
also said the embargo harms the Dominican Republic in view of
international accusations of "alleged violations" and by the
flow of Haitians.
  Herrera Cabral said the Dominican Government dedicates
virtually 25 million pesos ($2 million) a month to maintaining
border security.
  All of these inconveniences have been heightened in the past
months by the campaign for the upcoming general elections, which
will be held this coming Monday in the Dominican Republic.
  U.S. diplomatic sources, who chose to remain anonymous,
confirmed to EFE that the Dominican Government "suggested" to
the United States that it refrain from making "any move" on
Haiti before the Dominican elections.

</TEXT>

